He wistfully regrets that the days are past ‘ ante Petrum Lom- bardum,’ when men abstained from these futile hypotheses. He denies the wisdom, he even fears the sinfulness (page 228, 11110 15) of discussing them. Thus, although with one foot he stands in the Scholastic age, the other is secking a resting- place elsewhere. He has no patience with the puerile vanity, the love of novelty, the ainbition, the manifold discordances of the ‘ moderns': he cares for reality, fact, truth. What God, in fact, has done, that alone is real, is possible, is true (page 228).
